69. <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z300000078</ID><A1>Amory, Thomas, 1691?-1788?</A1><T1>John Buncle (1756)</T1><PBL>Printed for J. Noon, [etc.]</PBL><Y1>1756</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd3>
<body>
<p> <edit>[Side note: <bytes>1Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="FN000180"><s>Account of the author of the famous book de libe tate ecclesiastica. </s></note><s>Another extraordinary book I saw in
this library, was the famous piece <hi r="italic">de libertate
ecclesiastica,</hi> written against the papal usurpations,
at the time his holiness, <hi r="italic">Camille
Borghense,</hi> commonly called <hi r="italic">Paul</hi> V, had the
memorable contest with the <hi r="italic">Venetians</hi>; and
upon enquiring, who was the author of this
scarce and valuable work; that was superior
even to Father Paul's book upon the same
subject, in defence of the liberties of mankind; 
Mr. <hi r="italic">Trenchard</hi> the president of the
society, shewed me <hi r="italic">Cappel's assertion of the
true Faith against Rosweius</hi> the <hi r="italic">jesuit</hi>. </s>
<s>And in it the following passage, pag. 17. </s>
<s>&mdash;In ecclesiastica antiquitate quam non
esset Tyro Casaubonus, docuit A. D. 1607.
libro singulari de libertate ecclesiastica,
cujus jam pagin&aelig; 264. typis erant edit&aelig;,
cum rex Henricus IV. </s><s>Compositis jam
Venetorum cum pontifice Romano controversiis,
vetuit ultra progredi, et hoc ipsum
quod fuerat inchoatum, supprimi voluit, ut
ejus pauca nunc extent exemplaria. </s><s><ps>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;And
in the same book, I saw some manuscript </ps>
<pb n="359">
<ps>references to <hi r="italic">Casaubon's lettres,</hi> p. 628. 632,
and 647. edit. Hag.&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;and to one place in
<hi r="italic">Scaliger's letters,</hi> p. 345. ed. 1627. </ps></s><s>&mdash; 
Several places I turned to, and saw that <hi r="italic">Casaubon</hi>
hinted to his friends, that he was the
author of the book De Ecclesiastica Antiquitate:
and that <hi r="italic">Scaliger</hi> affirmed it (32.) <edit>[Footnote 32: <bytes>6Kb</bytes>]</edit><note idref="FN000181">[32] <p><s>(32.) The great <hi r="italic">Joseph Scaliger</hi> was born Aug. 4.
1544, and died at Leyden the 21st of January, in the
65th year of his age, A. D. 1609. </s><s>His father, <hi r="italic">Julius
C&aelig;sar Scaliger,</hi> died in the 75th year of his age, October
21, 1558. </s></p>
<p><s>His <xref RID="10021001"> father was a papist: the son a protestant. </s><s>They
were both great men in the republic of letters, and both
writ many books: but the son was by far the greatest
man. </s></p>
<p><s>What I like best of the father's works, are his <hi r="italic">poeticks</hi>. </s>
<s>&mdash;His <hi r="italic">account of the Latin tongue</hi>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;and his <hi r="italic">exercitations
against Cardan</hi>. </s><s>These are fine pieces. </s><s>His <hi r="italic">problems
on Aulus Gellius</hi> is likewise a good thing. </s></p>
<p><s>The works of <hi r="italic">Joseph</hi> the son, are as follow&mdash; 
<hi r="italic">Commentarii in appendicem Virgilii. &mdash;Not&aelig; in librum
Varronis de re rustica.&mdash;Conjectur&aelig; in Varronem de
lingua Latina.&mdash;Castigationes in Valerium Flaccum.
&mdash;Not&aelig; in Tertullianum de Pallio, cum tractatur de
equinoctiis.&mdash;Loci cujusdam Galeni difficillimi explicatio.
&mdash;Elenchus Trib&aelig;resii Nicolai Serarii.&mdash;Confutatio
ejusdem Serarii animadversorum in Scaligerum.&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;Castigationes
et not&aelig; in Eusebii chronica.&mdash;Thesaurus temporum.
&mdash;Elenchus utriusque orationis chronologic&aelig; Davidis
Par&aelig;i.&mdash;Conjectanea de Nonni Dionystaticis.&mdash; 
Not&aelig; in opera Ausonii.&mdash;Emendatio temporum.&mdash;Veterum
Gr&aelig;corum fragmenta.&mdash;Cyclometrica elementa duo.
&mdash;Appendix ad Cyclometriam suam.&mdash;Ausoniarum lectionum
libri duo.&mdash;Emendationes ad Theocriti, etc. Idyllia.
&mdash;Not&aelig; in Hippocratem.&mdash;Not&aelig; et castigationes in
Tibullum, Catullum, Propertium.&mdash;Epistolarum volumen.
&mdash;Commentarii in Manilium.&mdash;Animadversiones in
Melchioris Guillandini commentarium in tria Plinii de
papyro capita.&mdash;Epistola adversus barbarum et indoctum
poema patroni clientis Lucani.&mdash;Diatriba de decimis
in lege Dei.&mdash;Notitia Galli&aelig;.&mdash;Diatriba de
Europ&aelig;orum linguis, etc.&mdash;Judicium de quadam Thesi
chronologica.&mdash;Expositio numismatis argenter Constantini
imperatoris.&mdash;Orphei poet&aelig; hymni sacri versibus antiquis
Latine expressi.&mdash;Martialis select. epigram. Versiones
Gr&aelig;ce.&mdash;Sophoclis Ajax characteri vetere conversus.
&mdash;In &AElig;schyli Prometheum prologus. &mdash;Animadversiones
in epigrammata, etc. Cornelii Galli.&mdash;Animadversiones
in Cyclopem Euripidis.&mdash;Dionysius Cato cum
n&oacute;tis.&mdash;De equinoctiorum anticipatione diatriba.&mdash; 
Varia poemata Latina.&mdash;Poemata Gr&aelig;ca versa ex Latino,
etc.&mdash;Not&aelig; in panegyricum ad Pisones. &mdash;Castigatio
kalendarii Gregoriani.&mdash;Interpretatio proverbiorum
Arabicorum cum scholiis.&mdash;De arte critica diatriba.&mdash; 
Not&aelig; in novum testamentum.&mdash;Hyppoliti canon paschalis,
cum commentariis.&mdash;De re nummaria dissertatio.
&mdash;Discours de la jonction des mers, etc.&mdash; 
Discours sur milice Romaine.&mdash;Lettres touchant l'explication
de quelques medailles.&mdash;Pr&aelig;fatio in origines lingu&aelig; 
Latin&aelig;.&mdash;Scaligerana.&mdash;Epistola in Fabrium
Paulinum.&mdash;Animadversiones in locos controversos Roberti
Titii.&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;Vita Julii Cesaris Scaligeri cum epistola de
vetustate et splendore gentis Scaligera.</hi> </s></p>
<p><s>These are the works of <hi r="italic">Joseph Scaliger,</hi> and in them
one meets with so various and fine an erudition, and
so much valuable criticism, that if the reader of fortune
will take my advice, he will get them all into his closet
as soon as possible; and at the same time, the four excellent
pieces I have mentioned of <hi r="italic">Julius Cesar Scaliger,</hi>
the <hi r="italic">father</hi> of <hi r="italic">Joseph</hi>. </s></p>
<p><s>N. B. The great <hi r="italic">Lewis Cappel,</hi> author of the <hi r="italic">assertion
of the true faith,</hi> was a protestant minister at <hi r="italic">Saumur</hi>. </s>
<s>He was born October 14, 1583, and died at <hi r="italic">Saumur,</hi>
the 16th of June, 1568, aged 75. </s><s>He was likewise
the author of that excellent book called, <hi r="italic">Arcanum
punctuationis revelatum</hi>; and of another very valuable
thing, called <hi r="italic">Critica Sacra</hi>. </s></p>
<p><s>His son, <hi r="italic">Jean Cappel,</hi> turned <hi r="italic">papist,</hi> and died a despicable
<hi r="italic">apostate</hi> in the <hi r="italic">Romish</hi> church. </s></p>
<p><s>N. B. There were two other <hi r="italic">Cappels,</hi> protestant
ministers; both <hi r="italic">Jacques,</hi> who died in 1585&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;and
1624, and were the authors of several controversial
writings against popery: but they were weak writers in
respect of the learned <hi r="italic">Louis Cappel</hi>. </s></p></note> </s><s><ps>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash; </ps>
<pb n="360">
<ps>The words&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;<hi r="italic">Vetuit ultra progredi, et hoc
ipsum quod fuerat inchoatum supprimi voluit</hi>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash; 
accounts for this being published imperfect; 
which all that see it wonder at. </ps></s></p></body></div3>
