SECTION XIV. <attbytes>31Kb</attbytes><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>BOOK</TY><ID>Z300000242</ID><A1>Amory, Thomas, 1691?-1788?</A1><T1>John Buncle (1756)</T1><PBL>Printed for J. Noon, [etc.]</PBL><Y1>1756</Y1><T2>Literature Online</T2></comcitn></comhd3>
<front>
<lg><l>&indent;Bear me, ye friendly powers, to gentler scenes,</l>
<l>To shady bow'rs, and never&hyphen;fading greens;</l>
<l>To flow'ry meads, the vales, and mazy woods,</l>
<l>Some sweet soft seat, adorn'd with springs and floods:</l>
<l>Where with the muses, I may spend my days,</l>
<l>And steal myself from life by slow decays.</l>
<l>With age unknown to pain or sorrow blest,</l>
<l>To the dark grave retiring as to rest;</l>
<l>While gently with one sigh this mortal frame,</l>
<l>Dissolving turns to ashes whence it came;</l>
<l>And my freed soul departs without a groan;</l>
<l>In transport wings her flight to worlds unknown.</l></lg></front>
